<rfc ipr="full2026" docName="draft-flm-openpgp-sync-01">
  <front>
    <!-- Working title. We'll want something that more accurately frames the system before we submit. It never also hurts to have a more catchy title... -->
    <title abbrev="OpenPGP Key Subscriptions">Syncing OpenPGP Keys Across an Organization</title>

    <!-- I don't care about the order of authors. Note that IETF consisters all named authors to have contributed equally. Feel free to reorder if you'd like. -->
    <author initials="M.M." surname="McCain" fullname="R. Miles McCain">
      <organization abbrev="FLM">First Look Media</organization>
      <email>ietf@sendmiles.email</email>
      <uri>https://rmrm.io</uri>
    </author>
    <author initials="M.L." surname="Lee" fullname="Micah F. Lee">
      <organization abbrev="TI">The Intercept</organization>
      <email>micah.lee@theintercept.com</email>
      <uri>https://micahflee.com/</uri>
    </author>

    <date month="July" year="2018"/>
    <area>Security</area>

    <!-- Given that 'key management' is listed as a critical category of the 'Security' area, I believe that this I-D is best suited for the 'Security' area. -->

    <keyword>OpenPGP</keyword>
    <keyword>GPGSync</keyword>
    <keyword>GPG</keyword>
    <abstract>
      <!-- <t>Ensuring that all members of an organization have their colleagues' most recent PGP keys is critical to maintaining operational security. This document specifies a system by which OpenPGP clients may subscribe to an organization's key-list
      and -->
      keep its internal keystore up-to-date. To enable cross-client compatibility, this document proposes a standard format for the key-list file as well as feature requirements for OpenPGP clients who wish to implement this functionality.
    </t>
  </abstract>
  <note/>
</front>
<middle>
  <section anchor="intro" title="Introduction">
    <t>This document specifies a system by which OpenPGP clients may subscribe to a cryptographically signed key-list published by an organization. This system allows for seamless key rotation across an organization.</t>
  </section>
</middle>
<back></back>
</rfc>
